                    <head>
                        <title type="supplied" xml:lang="en">Ólafs saga Tryggvasonar and Old
                            Testament Additions</title>
                        <origPlace>Iceland</origPlace>
                        <origDate notBefore="1250" notAfter="1300" cert="high" evidence="conjecture">s. XIII 2/2</origDate>
                        <note>The manuscript contains the text of the Icelandic translation of the
                            Latin history of King Ólafr Tryggvason, written by <name type="person" key="OddSno001">Oddr Snorrason</name>, a monk of the Benedictine
                            monastery of <name type="place">Þingeyrar</name> in the <name type="place">northern Iceland</name>
                            <date>towards the end of the twelfth century</date>. There are also some
                            additional chapters which have apparently been taken from another Latin
                            History of Ólafr Tryggvason, written by <name type="person" key="GunLei001">Gunnlaugr Leifsson</name>, likewise a monk in the
                            monastery of <name type="place">Þingeyrar</name> (died about 1218). Page
                            99 has later additions: <title>Tú laga-orð guðs</title>, an Icelandic
                            version of the Ten Commandments, and <title>Tíu undr
                            Egiptalands</title>, a list of the ten plagues which led to the escape
                            of the Israelites from Egypt, a summary description of the crossing of
                            the Red Sea, and the Reception of the Law. When <name type="person" key="ArnMag001">Árni Magnússon</name> got the manuscript, it was
                            bound together with <ref>AM 68 fol</ref>
                  </note>
                    </head>
